<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🤖 AI001 Week 7 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Understanding the Code — Don't Just Build · <strong>Course:</strong> AI Coding with Replit Agent · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>If you use AI-built code without understanding it, you do not grow as a coder — you stay dependent on the AI. This week you learn the most powerful prompt of all: <strong>"Explain what each line does."</strong> Once you understand a piece of code, you can reuse it anywhere.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each prompt. Before the AI answers, write what kind of answer you expect to get back.</p>
<pre><code>Just make it work.
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Will this prompt teach you anything about how the code works? Why or why not?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code>Explain what each line of this code does, in Korean,
in words an elementary student could understand.
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What kind of answer will this give? How is it different from "just make it work"?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p>Look at this small piece of code:</p>
<pre><code>let score = 0;
button.addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
  score = score + 1;
  output.textContent = score;
});
</code></pre>
<p><strong>In your own words, what do you THINK this code does when you click the button?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Weak Prompt 🐛</h2>
<p>Each prompt below will not help the student actually understand their code. Read what the student <strong>wanted</strong>, then rewrite the prompt to get a clear, line-by-line explanation.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt A</strong> — The student wants to understand <strong>every line</strong> of a function, in simple words.</p>
<pre><code>What does this do?
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> ask it to go line by line, and ask for simple language.</p>
<p><strong>Write a stronger prompt:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is "line by line" better than "what does this do"?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Prompt B</strong> — The student understood the code, and now wonders if there is a <strong>simpler way</strong> to write it.</p>
<pre><code>Make new code.
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> ask "is there a simpler way to do this, and why?"</p>
<p><strong>Write a stronger prompt:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is asking "is there another way?" a good habit?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Prompt C</strong> — The student wants the AI to <strong>add a comment</strong> above each line so they can read it later.</p>
<pre><code>Comment the code.
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> say where the comments go (above each line) and what language they should be in.</p>
<p><strong>Write a stronger prompt:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why do comments help you reuse code later?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Understand Your Own Code 📸</h2>
<p>Open one of your projects. Pick a short piece of its code and ask the AI to <strong>explain each line</strong>. Read the explanation, then write your own short note above each line (in Korean or English) saying what it does.</p>
<p>When you finish, send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of your commented code, then explain what you learned. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The piece of code I picked does …</p>
<p>The AI explained that the first line …</p>
<p>A line I did not understand before was …</p>
<p>Now I know it does …</p>
<p>One thing I could reuse this code for is …</p>
<p>A question I still have is …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Teach It Back 🗒️</h2>
<p>Read your code out loud, line by line, in your own words — as if teaching someone next to you. Write your spoken explanation here. If you can explain it, you understand it.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + a photo (or video) of your commented code + your "teach it back" notes to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
<div class="footer">영어코딩 · <b>english-coding.co.uk</b></div>
</div></body></html>
